eople|Kung]] [[Taa language|\u01c3X\u00f3\u00f5]] || 1 || 40-70<ref name=\"Childs\"/>\n|-\n|[[Austronesian languages|Austronesian]] || [[Madagascar]] || [[Malagasy people|Malagasy]] || 20 || 1<ref>{{cite book |last1=Childs |first1=G. Tucker |title=An Introduction to African Languages |date=2003 |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |isbn=9027295883 |page=x |url=https://www.google.com/books?id=CJtcBtFyGJUC |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] || [[Central Africa]], [[East Africa]], [[North Africa]], [[Southern Africa]], [[West Africa]] || [[Afrikaners]], [[British diaspora in Africa|British]], [[French diaspora|French]] || 6 || 3<ref>{{cite book |last1=Childs |first1=G. Tucker |title=An Introduction to African Languages |date=2003 |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |isbn=9027295883 |pages=x, 206, 211 |url=https://www.google.com/books?id=CJtcBtFyGJUC |accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n! Total \n! Africa \n! \n! 1.2 billion (UN 2016) || c. 2,000<ref>The total number of languages natively spoken in Africa is variously estimated (depending on the delineation of [[language]] vs. [[dialect]]) at between 1,250 and 2,100.\n{{cite book|title=African Languages: an Introduction|editor-last=Heine|editor-first=Bernd|editor2-last=Heine|editor2-first=Bernd|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2000}}\nSome counts estimate \"over 3,000\", e.g. {{cite book|title=The Language of African Literature|page=ix|editor-last=Epstein|editor-first=Edmund L.|editor2-last=Kole|editor2-first=Robert|publisher=Africa World Press|year=1998|isbn=0-86543-534-0|quote= over 3,000 indigenous languages by some counts, and many creoles, pidgins, and lingua francas.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XkkrDH27jmIC&lpg=PP1&pg=PR9|accessdate=2011-06-23}}. Niger-Congo alone accounts for the majority of languages (and the majority of population), estimated at 1,560 languages by  [[SIL Ethnologue]]) ({{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=nigeria |title=Ethnologue report for Nigeria |work=Ethnologue Languages of the World}})</ref> \n|-\n|}\n\n===Major ethnic groups===\nThe following is a table of major ethnic groups (10 million people or more):\n{|class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Major ethnic groups\n!Region\n!Countries\n!Language family\n!Pop. (millions)<br/>(year)\n|-\n| [[Akan people|Akan]] || West Africa || [[Ghana]], [[Ivory Coast]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Kwa ||  {{sort|020|20}}{{year needed|date=May 2018}}\n|-\n|[[Abyssinian people|Abyssinians]] || Horn of Africa || [[Ethiopia]], [[Eritrea]] || Afro-Asiatic, Semitic||  \n|-\n|[[Amharas|Amhara]] || Horn of Africa || [[Ethiopia]] || Afro-Asiatic, Semitic||  {{sort|022|22}} (2007)  \n|-\n|[[Chewa people|Chewa]] || Central Africa || [[Malawi]], [[Zambia]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Bantu || {{sort|012|12}} (2007)\n|-\n|[[Fula people|Fulani]] || West Africa || [[Mauritania]], [[Gambia]]. [[Guinea-Bissau]], [[Guinea]], [[Nigeria]], [[Cameroon]], [[Senegal]], [[Mali]], [[Burkina Faso]], [[Benin]], [[Niger]], [[Chad]], [[Sudan]], [[CAR]], [[Ghana]], [[Togo]], [[Sierra Leone]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Senegambian||  {{sort|020|20}}{{year needed|date=May 2018}} \n|-\n|[[Hausa people|Hausa]] || West Africa || [[Nigeria]], [[Niger]], [[Benin]], [[Ghana]], [[Cameroon]], [[Chad]], [[Sudan]] || Afro-Asiatic, Chadic ||  {{sort|043|43}}{{year needed|date=May 2018}}\n|-\n|[[Hutu people|Hutu]] || Central Africa || [[Rwanda]], [[Burundi]], [[Democratic Republic of Congo]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Bantu || {{sort|015|15}}{{year needed|date=May 2018}}\n|-\n|[[Igbo people|Igbo]] || West Africa || [[Nigeria]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Volta\u2013Niger ||  {{sort|034|34}} (2017)\n|-\n|[[Kanuri people|Kanuri]] || Central Africa || [[Nigeria]],<ref name=\"The World Factbook: Nigeria\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ni.html|title=The World Factbook: Nigeria|accessdate=2013-12-31|work=[[World Factbook]]|publisher=[[Central Intelligence Agen