ara || Algeria, Libya, Morocco, Tunisia, Mali, Niger, Burkina Faso || 1.2 ||\n|-\n|[[Zaghawa people|Zaghawa]]|| Nilo-Saharan, Eastern Saharan || [[Zaghawa language|Zaghawa]] || Chad Basin || Chad, Sudan || 0.2 ||\n|-\n|}\n\n====West Africa====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Name\n! Family\n! Language\n! Region\n! Country\n! data-sort-type=\"number\"|Population (million)\n! Notes\n|-\n|[[Adele people|Adele]]|| Niger\u2013Congo, Gbe || [[Adele language|Adele]] || West || [[Ghana]]ian-[[Togo]] Borderlands || .05<ref>{{cite web |url=https://joshuaproject.net/clusters/181 |title=People Cluster:  Guinean |last= |first= |date=2018 |website=joshuaproject.net |publisher=[[Joshua Project]] |access-date=23 January 2018 |quote=}}</ref> || \n|-\n|[[Akan people|Akan]]|| Niger\u2013Congo, Kwa || [[Akan language|Akan]] || West || South Ghana, Ivory Coast || 20 || An ethnic group of related sub-groups. The largest subgroups are the [[Ashanti people|Ashanti]] and the [[Fante people|Fante]]\n|-\n|[[Aku people|Aku]]|| ([[English-based creole languages|Creole]]) || [[Aku dialect|Aku]] || West || [[Gambia]] || 0.01||\n|-\n|[[Baka (Cameroon and Gabon)|Baka]]|| Niger Congo, Ubangian||[[Baka language|Baka]] || West/Central || Southeastern [[Cameroon]], Northern [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]], Northern [[Gabon]] || 0.3-0.4 || The Baka are also known as Bebayaka, Bebayaga, or Bibaya, or (along with the other [[Mbenga people]]s) the derogatory Babinga.\n|-\n|[[Bambara people|Bambara]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Mande || [[Bambara language|Bambara]] || West || Mali || 3||\n|-\n|[[Bassa (Cameroon)|Basaa]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Bantu || [[Basaa language|Basaa]] || West || [[Cameroon]] || 0.2||\n|-\n|[[Bassa (Liberia)|Bassa]] || Niger\u2013Congo, Kru || [[Bassa language|Bassa]] || West ||Liberia || 0.3 ||\n|-\n|[[Beti-Pahuin]] ||Niger\u2013Congo, Bantu ||[[Ewondo language|Ewondo]], [[Fang people|Fang]], [[Bulu language|Bulu]] || West || Cameroon, Republic of the Congo, Equatorial Guinea, Gabon,